1:1 COMMENT "# atomic_call_temps.z -- demonstrates per-call atomic processing."
1:66 EOL "\n"
2:1 COMMENT "#"
2:2 EOL "\n"
3:1 COMMENT "# When a call's argument is a non-trivial expression (a projection,"
3:68 EOL "\n"
4:1 COMMENT "# a method call, a constructor), the typechecker hoists it into a"
4:66 EOL "\n"
5:1 COMMENT "# synth temp inside a per-call sub-scope. The temp's lock on the"
5:65 EOL "\n"
6:1 COMMENT "# source releases when that sub-scope pops, so back-to-back calls"
6:66 EOL "\n"
7:1 COMMENT "# on the same source compose without spurious lock conflicts."
7:62 EOL "\n"
8:1 COMMENT "#"
8:2 EOL "\n"
9:1 COMMENT "# This example exercises both mechanics:"
9:41 EOL "\n"
10:1 COMMENT "#   1. Two consecutive `use_reader r: f.myreader` calls succeed"
10:64 EOL "\n"
11:1 COMMENT "#      because each call's sub-scope releases the borrow on close."
11:67 EOL "\n"
12:1 COMMENT "#   2. Two args of one call, both derived from the same `f`, are"
12:65 EOL "\n"
13:1 COMMENT "#      attributed to the same call identity and merge correctly."
13:65 EOL "\n"
14:1 EOL "\n"
